on't want to waste my money on art supplies that i won't end up using, so please help me!<br>
<br>
okay, my first decision has to be whether to use tone sheets and make the comic b&amp;w, or whether to color it.  but that's not really a decision needing advice... i don't think... o.o<br>
<br>
anywho, i need to know if neopike markers work well.  ... i'm not that good at using photoshop to color, and perhaps that other program... ... paint... something... crap! i can't remember what it's called! anyways, perhaps it would be easier.  and maybe i should just take the effort to go through some tutorials!  *_* blarg... *lazy girl here*  (eep! i just watched &quot;Seven!&quot; NOO!!! I DON'T WANNA BE SLOTH!)<br>
<br>
wow, off topic.  anywho... HOW DO I COLOR!?!  or should i just try to find someone else who's already good at coloring? ... well, basically *i guess* my question would be &quot;are markers a crappy way to color manga?&quot;  now i get to the question! ^_^' <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dragonsallie>DragonSallie</A> at: 6/28/03 7:23 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=themightyservo>The Mighty Servo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/29/03 6:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5473.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://filebox.vt.edu/users/cmayer/images/servo.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: coloring... ah!</span><hr size=1> IMO, markers or tone sheets would be harder to get used to than Photoshop. If you've already got Photoshop, then they're also an added cost. <br>
<br>
If you'll be printing this comic, then B&amp;W would be a definite choice because of printing cost. If not, well, it's still sorta simpler than (good) color, so if you'll be constrained by time that could be a major consideration.<br>
<br>
Another consideration would perhaps be using Painter to color. You'd then have a program that acts like, and basically looks like, coloring by hand with markers (or watercolor, oil paint, etc). <br>
<br>
I'd recommend learning computer coloring. Putting in basic color isn't very hard at all (follow the PK tutorials or something), and you can extend that much further without extra costs in anything but time. From all I can see, comics on all levels are all moving to computer coloring, and some even computer inking.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=funkenstein@polykarbonbbs>Funkenstein</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://freespace.virgin.net/aggs.art/rionfunk.gif width=81 height=100" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/29/03 7:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5473.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://freespace.virgin.net/aggs.art/funk.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: coloring... ah!</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START >: --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/mad.gif ALT=">:"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> random comics tip:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
